  "signature": "ed25519:7b2d4f8a1c3e6b9d0f2a5c8e1b4d7f0a3c6e9b2d5f8a1c4e7b0d3f6a9c2e5b8",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial FEA solver (Ansys Mechanical) used with documented version control; FDA in-house code subject to institutional SQA procedures per 21 CFR Part 11.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 was employed under a validated commercial software license. The FDA in-house FEA code is maintained under a documented SQA plan aligned with institutional IT governance. Version identifiers, input decks, and solver logs are archived in a controlled repository. No custom solver modifications were introduced. SQA level 2 is appropriate for medium model risk with commercially validated solver infrastructure."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions used to verify element formulations relevant to contact and large-displacement bending.",
      "rationale": "Standard ASME V&V 10 benchmark problems for beam bending and contact mechanics were executed against Ansys Mechanical and the FDA solver. Results agreed with analytical solutions to within 0.5% for linear elastic cases and within 2.1% for nonlinear contact cases. Element formulations (SOLID186 for screw, CONTA174/TARGE170 for interfaces) are well-established in peer-reviewed literature for orthopedic implant simulation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change of less than 5% between successive refinements.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted on the pedicle screw shank and rod-clamp interface regions. QoI (stiffness, yield force) changed by less than 2.3% between the medium and fine mesh, confirming adequate convergence. The production mesh (approximately 148,000 elements) was selected as the converged configuration. Discretization error is bounded and does not materially influence the validation comparison."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Force and displacement residuals converge to below 0.1% of applied load at each load step; energy norm monitored throughout.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear solution used full Newton-Raphson iteration with automatic time-stepping. Force residual norm fell below 0.05% of the applied reference load at every converged increment. No diverged load steps were observed. Energy norm remained monotonically decreasing. Solver error is considered negligible relative to material and geometric variability in the experimental dataset."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments completed by a second analyst not involved in primary model development.",
      "rationale": "A senior biomechanical engineer independent of the primary modeling team reviewed all input decks, boundary condition definitions, material property assignments, and contact pair settings. Discrepancies identified during review (minor inconsistency in rod pre-load magnitude) were corrected prior to the validation comparison runs. The review process is documented in the project technical record."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model captures nonlinear yielding of Ti-6Al-4V; contact formulation reproduces load transfer at screw-rod and rod-clamp interfaces consistent with published experimental observations.",
      "rationale": "A bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity model (E=114 GPa, yield stress=880 MPa, tangent modulus=2.1 GPa) was assigned to the Ti-6Al-4V screw and rod, consistent with ASTM F136 material specifications and literature-reported tensile test data. Augmented Lagrangian contact with a friction coefficient of 0.2 was applied at all metal-on-metal interfaces, consistent with prior tribological characterization for dry titanium contact. The model form is appropriate for the quasi-static, large-displacement loading regime of ASTM F1717."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric dimensions sourced from certified material certificates and dimensional inspection reports for the specific production lot used in testing.",
      "rationale": "Material certificates for the Ti-6Al-4V production lot were obtained from DePuy Synthes and confirmed compliance with ASTM F136. Dimensional inspection of screw geometry (outer diameter, thread pitch, core diameter) was performed on three representative screws from the test lot using a Zeiss CMM; deviations from nominal were less than 0.03 mm and were incorporated into the FEA geometry. Polyaxial screw head seating torque was measured and applied as a pre-load boundary condition. Input uncertainty is formally quantified and propagated through the validation metric."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test constructs from a single production lot; dimensional and material traceability documented.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs were assembled from a single production lot of non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws and 5.5 mm titanium rods. All screws and rods were traceable to the same material certificate. Construct assembly was performed by a trained technician following the manufacturer's surgical technique guide. Testing was distributed across two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH and an ISO 17025-accredited external facility) to assess inter-laboratory reproducibility. The N=11 sample size provides adequate statistical power for the E/uval metric used in the output comparison."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios, including at minimum two distinct load levels or boundary condition configurations representative of the intended use environment.",
      "rationale": "All validation testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 test configuration: quasi-static compression-bending at a crosshead displacement rate of 5 mm/min, with a 100 mm inter-fixture distance and a fixed offset block geometry. While the ASTM F1717 protocol is the regulatory gold standard for pedicle screw construct evaluation, only this single loading configuration was exercised in the validation campaign. The team considered this sufficient given that: (1) ASTM F1717 is the FDA-recognized consensus standard for this device class; (2) the model has been previously exercised in torsional loading configurations for analogous cannulated screw designs with comparable accuracy; and (3) the medium decision consequence classification reduces the stringency of evidence required for acceptance. Expert judgment from three independent biomechanical engineers concurred that the single-condition validation, combined with the breadth of the output comparison across three QoIs and two laboratories, provides adequate confidence for the intended regulatory submission context. Formal multi-condition testing was deferred to the next development phase."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions and material inputs are demonstrably equivalent to experimental test conditions; any discrepancies are quantified and their effect on QoI is assessed.",
      "rationale": "Experimental boundary conditions (fixture geometry, applied displacement, pre-load torque) were measured and directly replicated in the FEA model. The 100 mm inter-fixture distance was confirmed by caliper measurement on each construct prior to testing. Rod pre-load was applied in the FEA as a bolt pre-tension element calibrated to the measured screw head seating torque (4 Nm). Sensitivity analyses demonstrated that ±10% variation in seating torque changes predicted stiffness by less than 1.8%, confirming that the input equivalency uncertainty does not materially affect the validation outcome."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative validation metric E/uval < 1.96 for all primary QoIs; mean absolute percentage error < 10%.",
      "rationale": "Three primary QoIs were compared: construct stiffness (E/uval=0.91, MAPE=4.2%), yield force (E/uval=1.44, MAPE=6.8%), and force at 40 mm displacement (E/uval=1.12, MAPE=5.5%). All three metrics satisfy both acceptance criteria. The validation uncertainty (uval) incorporates experimental measurement uncertainty, inter-laboratory variability, and model input uncertainty propagated via a first-order Taylor series expansion. The output comparison is considered thorough and the quantitative evidence strongly supports model adequacy for the stated COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly correspond to the regulatory submission endpoints and are mechanistically linked to the clinical failure modes of interest.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three primary endpoints specified in ASTM F1717 and are the quantities reported in the regulatory submission. Yield force is directly linked to the risk of permanent construct deformation under physiological loading; force at 40 mm displacement characterizes ultimate load-bearing capacity prior to catastrophic failure. All three QoIs are mechanistically relevant to the clinical failure mode (screw fracture or rod fracture leading to loss of spinal fixation and revision surgery)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities are conducted on the same device design, material, and loading configuration as the intended COU; any differences are explicitly documented and their impact assessed.",
      "rationale": "The validation activities were conducted on the identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design and production lot as the device subject to the regulatory submission. The ASTM F1717 test configuration used in validation is the same configuration modeled in the FEA and is the standard accepted by FDA for this device class. No surrogate materials or simplified geometries were employed in the validation testing. The validation activities are therefore directly relevant to the COU without material qualification gaps."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team has reviewed all 13 V&V 40 credibility factors and determined that the overall body of evidence is sufficient to support acceptance of the FEA model for the stated COU. Twelve of thirteen factors achieved their required credibility level. The single exception — Test conditions (achieved level 2, required level 3) — reflects the use of a single ASTM F1717 loading configuration in the validation campaign. The team considered this shortfall in the context of the full evidence package and concluded, on balance, that it does not preclude acceptance. The ASTM F1717 protocol is the FDA-recognized consensus standard for pedicle screw construct evaluation, and all three primary QoIs passed the quantitative validation metric (E/uval < 1.96) with comfortable margin. The output comparison factor, which directly captures model predictive accuracy, was assessed at the required level 3. Prior validation experience with analogous cannulated screw designs under multiple loading configurations provides supplementary confidence in the model's generalizability. The medium model risk level and medium decision consequence classification further support a risk-proportionate acceptance decision. The team acknowledges that multi-condition validation would strengthen the evidence base and recommends this activity for the next development phase, but judges that the current evidence is adequate for the intended regulatory submission purpose.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
